But officially, it was a staff assistance visit team.
OK. Today is, what is it, the 26th?
Didn't even look at the calendar, for heaven's sakes.
23rd.
OK, 23rd.
This is the third interview with General Cargill.
We talked last time about what he felt was the period in his career in which
He had the largest contribution to the service.

And now I'd like to turn it around and ask if there was a period in your military career in which you felt that you didn't have much of a contribution, or maybe you could have done something, but you couldn't, for some reason, get it through.
You couldn't be effective, maybe a shortcoming.
I would say that the time of least effectiveness for me
as far as being a reservist, and I think this is probably true of most people in the program at that time, was the period in which we had no equipment and no real wartime mission, so to speak.
The days of what we called the Little Red Schoolhouse days.
That's when we would meet in the basement of the old post office down in Bryan and watch old World War II and pre-World War II films.
would take correspondence courses and work bills and so forth.
But as far as being prepared to go to war and fulfill a specific wartime mission, we had none.
We had no preparation for that.
About all we had to offer was maybe some past active duty experience and probably a little bit better than average familiarization with world conditions, with our military
objectives and what have you.
But not much more than that.
You take almost a man off the street that was well read on current events would probably have as much ability to perform a service then as we had as reservists.
But that that was when I considered the program to be at rock bottom.
And then as I've mentioned in earlier conversations, it got better and better and better until the day
Not only do we have wartime missions, but we have brand new equipment in many cases right off the assembly line to perform those wartime missions.
So it's gone from absolute depths to what I feel is the best of all worlds.
So from the 50s to the 80s.
That's pretty well the time frame.
That's not to say we have everything we need in the way of equipment and funding, but I would say the things that we need are in probably the
approximate proportions is the thing that the active duty establishment needs.
In other words, we're getting our fair share of the assets from DOD.
What secretaries of defense do you think were most responsible for this upgrading?
At that time, I was so far down on the totem pole that I didn't even know who the secretary of defense was for the most part.
I do feel that
Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara had more to do with the degradation of the military establishment than any Secretary of Defense that pops in my mind.
We called him Mac the Knife because he was cutting funds for this, cutting funds for that.
We didn't need this.
We didn't need that.
And during his administration, the defense establishment deteriorated drastically in this country.
I think our present Secretary of Defense, Casper Weinberger, is just absolutely tops.
Can't say enough good things about him.
He fights hard for what we need.
I would say that those would be the two extremes.
The rest of them would be a shady grade between the two.
Now let's talk about a couple of those weapon systems that have been very controversial for the last few years.
And I'd just like your opinion on how you stand.
What about the B-1 bomber?
We should have had it years ago.
However,
In the delay, there's always a silver lining to every cloud, I guess.

The fact that some technological advances were made during the time the B-1 was on hold and was being delayed so that the B-1 we have, when it comes off the assembly line, will be a better weapon system than the B-1 that would have come off had Jimmy Carter and others not postponed it.
So there may be some blessings involved there.
But the B-52...
Well, you can go to Davis-Monthan, the boneyard of the Air Force Base, and you'll see acres of B-52s.
More going on all the time.
So we've not replaced those B-52s that have worn out, and those that are still flying, for the most part, are much older than any of the crew members on board flying them.
They were built and were flying before any of those people were born.
And, you know, things change.
You can say, well, you can just patch an old car so long.
Well, if you keep spending the right kind of money on it, you can keep it going indefinitely, I guess.
But there's no question in my mind that the B-1 is overdue and desperately needed by this country.
OK, I was reading Jimmy Carter's memoirs, and in that, in keeping faith, and in that, he says that he decided to veto the B-1 because of the crew's missile system.
And we could drop the crews out of the B-52.
And so we could modify in that sense.
And he also says that the effectiveness of a bomber trying to get into the Soviet Union would be almost a suicide mission for any pilot.
How would you respond to that?
Not being an operational type, I really couldn't address those points at all.
That would really take someone involved in the flying end of the thing.
As I mentioned to you earlier, I'm not a rated pilot.
I've never done any flying.
I've never studied operational tactics.
So I would just have to comment generally that since a manned bomber is the only
A fail-safe device we've got, once you send a manned bomber on a mission, you can always recall it, but you can't recall a missile once you push the button.
I would say that I would think our chances would be much better in a B-1 than in a B-52 if we had to go to war.

And I think we owe it to our military people and to our own country that we need to have the best odds that we've got, even though they may not be good odds, they'd still be the better odds than we have with a B-52.
I'm not so sure that Carter's assumption that we can't make it to a target in a manned bomber is a good assumption.
Our planners apparently think we can, or they wouldn't be building it.
Okay, I want to ask you about another system, and that's the missiles, the MX missile.
I'd like your opinion on that.
Should we deploy them?
I think a lot of it depends on the Russians.

I think a lot of it depends on the Pershing cruise missiles, the Glickhams ground launch cruise missiles and the Alchems air launch and different things and what effect they have, if any, on the talks in Geneva.
I think there's still a remote possibility that the MX, we may not have to deploy the MX.
The ALCOMs and the GLICOMs and so forth, SLICOMs for sea launch.
They've got all kinds of acronyms.
You've got to learn a whole new language to talk to these people.
But anyway, if those have the effect that I think they might have, it may be that we may be able to either delay or cut back on the scope of the MX.
I think we're always going to need some long-range ballistic missile capability.
I think to answer the question, yes, we need the MX, but I'm not sure we need it in the magnitude and in the scope that probably has been envisioned.
And all that depends on what reaction we get from the Russians on our cruise missiles.
Okay.
Speaking of the Russians, I'd like your opinion on the SALT talks, which, of course...
Republican and Democratic presidents supported until Mr. Reagan and then he started the START talks.
What was your feeling on the SALT agreement?
I felt you could put the same amount of reliance on that as well as on any other agreements we've ever signed with Russia.
And that is that they will honor it only when it's to their advantage to do so.
I don't think it's worth the paper it's written on.
That's not to say I don't think it's worth the effort.
I think we need to continue the effort.
I think we need to reach all the agreements we can on limiting.
The verifiable portion of the thing is extremely important.

But as far as a treaty being something we can say, hey, we've got a treaty, we can sit back and relax now, I think that that's, you know, even a man on the street that's not familiar with the situation would know you can't do that.
So I think that, yes, we should pursue the treaty talks.
And yes, we should get the best deal we can.
We should get it in writing, get everybody's agreement.
And we should live up to our end of the treaty and then see to it that they live up to their end.
But by the same token, if they don't, then we need some fallback position.
We need to assume they're not going to honor the treaty.
We need to make that basic assumption.
And it's a good assumption.
History's proven that.
So that's my feeling on that.
turn now to the role of leadership and the issue of leadership at A&M.

We pride ourselves on developing leaders and therefore I'd like to ask you, a leader both in the business and in the military field, what are the qualities, what are the values that make a good leader?
I think first of all you have to have average intelligence.
I don't
I don't feel that it's necessary to have an extremely high IQ.
In fact, in some cases, that might be a disadvantage.

But I think an average person with an average intelligence that's been trained from early childhood in the importance of self-reliance and the old Boy Scout law of all the trustworthy, loyal, helpful, friendly, courteous, kind, obedient, cheerful, thrifty, brave, clean, reverent type things, all those are
You know, they may get to be almost rote, but still each one of them individually is very important in developing leadership.
I think you have to develop a pretty high degree of self-reliance, and I think that's done only through experiencing a certain amount of adversity.
I think that if you don't have hardships and trials and tribulations that come along in smaller doses as you're young and it gets larger and larger as you grow,
If you're shielded from those, either by parents, peers, or what have you, it's much of a disservice.
Because in later life, when you are thrust in a leadership position and you do find yourself in a position of adversity, then you're not equipped to handle it.
But I feel that A&M does that.
I think that the student body, the discipline that we talked about earlier in the core,
by its very nature, imposes a certain amount of uneasiness.
It's the grain of sand and the oyster that develops into a pearl.
It's an abrasive process.
I think those are very important.
I think we have that here at A&M.
I think we try to develop that through giving people an opportunity to run for student office.
It's not a pleasant thing to run for the student senate.
It's a lot of hard work, and you take a lot of knocks, but it's a growing process.
And those that adapt to it and realize that that's part of the price they pay for being a leader and are willing to pay that price, well, then those things follow most of their life.
If you had to go back, I want to ask a similar question now.
If you had to go back to the Corps and they wanted you to give them a lecture on how to become a leader, what would you tell them?

I would tell them pretty well some of the things that I just told you there, plus the fact that I would try to emphasize to them to force themselves to accept positions of responsibility or to do actions which are responsible actions, even though it may be uncomfortable at the time.
They may not want to go out on a fundraising drive for the Boy Scouts, or they may not want to get involved with some of the
The civic service type of activities are available to some of our students.
But they need to force themselves to do that, even though it would be much more pleasant to get a six pack and go to the river fishing with the guys.
It's the old idea of learn to do by doing.
You learn to be a leader by being a leader.
And there are lots of opportunities on this campus and in life in general for people to place themselves in leadership roles.
We hear the expression all the time in all kinds of meetings, do we have any volunteers for this?
Or would someone volunteer to do this, that, or the other?
Volunteer.
Get involved.
Be part of it.
Do something.
And those little experiences continue to grow, and they develop a mindset that will follow you most of your life.
So I would advise them to get very active in core activities, in student activities, and in classroom activities.
Join every club they can find to join that they're eligible for.
Run for office.

responsibility and then they'll be a leader I was wondering if there's a difference between a business leader or a university leader or a military leader is there a difference in the way that those two types of people lead you're in a unique situation here so you should be yeah I think that
to answer your question, I don't think there's a dime's worth of difference in leadership in any of those.
I think that it all goes back to some very basic principles that a lot of times we forget.
Things that you learn in management 101, the importance of unity of command, having one boss, one guy that can make a decision and then take the heat if it's necessary for him to take it.
Span of control, not having too many people working for him.
Homogeneous assignment, getting people to
giving people work to do that's of a like nature so that you don't ask him to do one thing and then the next minute you ask him to do something that he's not really qualified to do.

Delegation of authority, I say, probably is the most important thing that a leader needs to develop in any of these arenas that you're talking about, whether it be military, civic, legislative, business, education, whatever.
A leader just does not have enough time during the day to do all he needs to do.
So you get your work done through people.
It comes down to what I like to refer to as my very favorite definition of management.
How do you define management?
Of course, that's one of the things that you always have in management classes.
What is management?
To me, management is defining and solving problems through the development and utilization of personnel.
If you do the job yourself,
You're not a manager.
You do the job through other people.
And to me, those basic things are true no matter what.
Have you ever read the book by former Brigadier General Douglas Kennard entitled The War Managers?
No.
It deals with Vietnam, and he did a survey of the 180 different generals who at one time were in Vietnam, and about 110 or so filled out the survey and sent it back to him.
And he deals with this issue of managing the army versus leading the army, and he sees differences here.
And of course, it could be managing the Air Force versus leading.
And he feels that one of the main problems in Vietnam and in the service is that so many people have MBAs, and so many people are managers, and there aren't as many true leaders.
Let's just go out and we've got to face the enemy now.
How would you respond to that?
Well, I would think that, of course, a lot of times,
If you've got a crisis situation on your hands, then I get involved.
I get on the telephone.
I take care of things myself rather than delegate.
I would think that when you're in a combat environment, it's very similar to me having a fire in the basement of the student center.
When they call me up and tell me we've got a major fire in the basement of the student center, I don't think about delegating.
I get on the phone.
I carry a bunch of phone numbers in my billfold of people I need to contact to make things happen.
I forget the chain of command, and I take care of the business.
And I would think that's where you'd have to be in combat.
But those situations probably occupy 1 tenth of 1% of your time.
The other 99.5% or whatever, then you can be a manager as opposed to a leader.
I don't really differentiate that much between managership and leadership.
I think they're almost synonymous terms.
So I would say that in a life-threatening or a combat environment situation that
that you'd have to throw some of your 101 rules out the window and do what the immediate situation called for, whatever it may be.
Now, maybe this is part of military mythology, but we often see on television and in the movies the military leader as the patent type.
let's kick him in the butt and go, guys, that kind of stuff.
I've never met but one guy that kind of fits that pattern.
He's retired, and he retired under adverse conditions named General Keegan.

He used to be in charge of Air Force Intelligence Service, and he made a number of speeches and took a number of positions that were counter to policy at that time, and so basically he really got fired.
Since then, he's been on a speaking tour, and I presume still is, of
Anybody can get to listen to him about the Russian threat and so forth.
He was a hellfire and brimstone patent type.
I've never met any other general that was like that.
So that's a myth, I think, for the most part.
However, in a wartime situation, it may take something like that.
And it's always good to have the ability to come unglued if you have to to get something done.
But you just don't want to use it until it's really necessary.
I think most of us have a
boiling point.
Some of us is lower than others and I think it should be a low point but I think all of us should have the ability to ball if the situation calls for it.
Okay, let's turn to General Rutter.
Did you know General Rutter?
I knew him personally.
Well, could you just describe him, the type of person that he was and your feelings toward him?
He was all the things that I've talked about is
what I think a leader should be.
He was personable.
He was friendly.
He was tough.
He was fair.
He could be nasty if the situation really demanded it, but only if the situation really demanded it.
He liked people.
He liked folksy things.
He liked to talk about some of his background, some of his experiences.
He liked for things to be run on a business-like basis with black ink at the bottom of the page instead of red ink.
He got a little bit more involved in some of the details of the university operation than probably he should have, but he did it not because he felt that others couldn't do it.
He did it because he liked to do it.

For example, when I was promoted, when I was hired as manager of the Texas A&M bookstore, I didn't get the offer until I personally went over and sat down for about an hour interview with General Rutter, and we talked.
He said, what makes you think you can run that bookstore?

And to me, it's a good job and a nice job and a big job, but it's not one where the president of the university would normally sit down with an hour interview and personally pass on the guy that's going to go in as the manager of the bookstore.
That would be done certainly no higher than the vice presidential level and probably not even at that level in today's environment.
Of course, at that time, the school was much smaller, so that might have had some bearing.
But he used to really get involved in a lot of,
personnel actions, especially for jobs where people were being hired to fill jobs, middle management and above.
You didn't hire anybody on this campus without his personal blessings.
And he wanted to interview people most of the time.
But I'm not saying that that's a drawback.
I'm just saying that in today's environment, with the numbers of people and the size of the university, you just couldn't do that.
No.
Well, just out of curiosity, what did you say to him?
I said, you bet I can.
I was very positive, and I think that's one of the things that got his attention.
There was never any vacillation or hesitation on my part.
Could I run the store?
I'd, of course, been with Sears Roebuck for eight years, so I'd had a good, solid background in retail business and in a profit-making type situation.
He had a great deal of respect for Sears, and I think my experience and the way I came across in the interview, apparently, was positive or I wouldn't have had the job.
But he used to go out and circulate on the campus quite a bit.
I know he came in to the bookstore for briefings periodically on our profit picture and how we were making things.
And that's pretty low level for the president to take time to come out and sit down in the bookstore manager's office and let the manager tell you how things were going in the bookstore.
But he was a dynamic guy.
He had tremendous respect.
And although I didn't know too much about this side of General Rutter,
I understand that he probably had a better handle on how politics works and the power maneuvers that you need to make in Austin for budget purposes and so forth about as well as anybody ever has.
Of course, being a state land commissioner for a long time, on the Austin scene, he knew how Austin worked.
He knew which buttons to push to get the reaction that he wanted, and he didn't hesitate to push them.
And I'm not saying that that's anything good, because we're a political organization.
entity, and we can't ever forget that.
You can paint a big state university, any color you want to paint it, it's still a political animal.
And it thrives on appropriations.
And appropriations are driven by politics, and politics is what he was a master at.
He really knew how to play it.
And he was a visionary.
He had visions of this university doing pretty well what it has done.
This complex we're in now was pretty well thought up and dreamed up and put into motion during his administration.
And just a super guy.
Very friendly.
I always thought the world of him.
I have a very close relationship with his widow, Mrs. Rutter.
I see her frequently.
But of course, during his administration, probably the most dynamic changes took place with the College of Texas A&M to the Texas A&M University.
And I'd like to ask your opinion on some of these changes.
What about as a former corpsman watching the end of the mandatory corps?
How did you feel about that?
I had mixed emotions.
My heart told me no, and my head told me yes.
That no, I hate to turn loose to the old ways of doing things.
That is A&M to me.
The core and A&M were synonymous terms at that time.
But logic would tell you that it had to happen.
And since it's happened, and since we've gotten used to it, there's no question that it was the appropriate thing to do.
I think that three things have happened.
that have brought A&M to the forefront.
One is the name change that you've already alluded to.
Second is the elimination of mandatory core.
And third is the admission of females to the university.
That's the next question.
Without any one of those three things having happened, we wouldn't be in the enviable position we're in today.
So did you feel about the same way about women?
I would say, Rob, doing away with mandatory core and admitting women, my feelings were exactly the same.
I knew it had to come.
It was obvious that it was coming.
But I still hated to give up the old way of doing things.
But I think that's human nature.
You just inertia.
You just hate to, you know, when you're going down a certain path and you're comfortable with it, no matter how strong the evidence may be that you need to change, you hate to change.
And so I had, I can't say I had any problems with it.
It's just that there was a certain nostalgia involved in seeing the,
the thing changed.
But it changed so gradually that it really wasn't bad.
Now, it appeared to be gradual to me because I was here on the scene.
And I see a few women this semester and a few more next semester and a few more next semester.
But to someone that was out in the boondocks that maybe thought or had contact with A&M say over two years, to him it was almost an instant change.
So it probably didn't impact me as much as it did some of the guys out in the business world that didn't have that much direct contact with the university.
But no question, it was the appropriate thing to do.
It was not done lightly and at the whims of some one individual.
It was done after much study.
And it had to come.
Do you remember, did General Rutter ever tell you about heat that he was getting from former students on this?
Never told me directly, but I understand from conversation around the campus that he did take a tremendous amount of heat.
That's, once again, where the mental conditioning and toughening that I talked about earlier.
He had been in situations all of his life in which he had to take criticism.
So he was equipped to handle criticism.
Now, nobody ever likes to be criticized, but you can handle it.
And if you've not been conditioned to handle it, then you just cave in.
You can't handle it.
So he was equipped to handle it.
Some people say that only a man of his stature could have brought these changes abroad.
What would you say about that?
I think probably these conditions would have come about if we hadn't even had a president.
It was just inevitable that these things happened.
I think his presence and his personal popularity
made the transition much easier, especially with some of our old die-hard former students.
They had such great respect for him that they would more or less think, well, I don't like it, but if Earl's there and he says let's do it, I'll go because of Earl, not because I agree with him.
But it might not have happened quite as soon.
It might not have happened quite as smoothly.
But all three of these things, I think, were inevitable, whether Rudder had been here or not.
But I do think that his presence and his support of them made the medicine go down a little bit more easily.
Now I'd like to ask about blacks and allowing blacks into A&M.
What was your opinion on that?
I don't think that there's my personal opinion is that it really hadn't had an adverse impact in any way whatsoever.
I think that the biggest problem we have is that we've not been able to attract enough of them.
Obviously, with the affirmative action thrust that the university has and has had since day one, not only with blacks but with Hispanics and other minority groups that we're trying to attract.
Obviously, we want to attract the best students possible regardless of color, race, what have you.
Other universities are in competition with the bright young students, whatever race.
And we've just not been successful in attracting the numbers of blacks that I feel that we should have.
But as far as their impact on core life, on campus life, I think it's been nothing but positive.
I think when you come to the university, you look for a broadening experience.
You look for finding ways to broaden your own horizon.
And the way you do that is by rubbing up against the world.
And we're a little...
microcosm, so to speak, of the world here.
We've got people from, well, not every country in the world, obviously, but from a lot of different countries.
And by meeting and being thrown with these people, they learn from you, you learn from them.
And you learn that possibly your narrow viewpoint of life is not the only one there is, and may not even be the best one there is.
So I feel that there's been a positive influence
And I'm all for it, and we need to do everything we can to continue in that direction.
Why do you think we have not been able to attract as many minority students as you would like to see?
I think it goes back to some of the traditional discriminatory policies that have existed primarily in the South over the past 20, 30 years, which the school segregation
And the quality of high school graduates is reflected in SAT scores and things of that type.
The students coming up through an all-black school system just weren't equipped to be competitive.
And it's a competitive world we live in.
You can pass all the laws you want to, but it comes right down to competition.
And I feel that now that integration is a fact of life in our elementary and secondary
school system that you're going to see more and more people, more and more blacks that will be in a position to be competitive than they have been in the past.
I think the reason A&M has not done better is that and I don't think the black students want us to do this.
We've not chosen to lower our standards just to attract a large number of black students.
We've maintained our standards and the numbers of black students that can meet our standards are
and are small in number, and they're highly sought after, not only from schools within the state, but from schools outside the state.
So the competition for high school graduates with high SAT scores that are black is unbelievable.
And we don't want just bodies.
We want quality students, whatever the color may be.
And the present policy is that we don't want to lower our standards in order to attract X numbers of minority students.

We feel that now that the high school graduates, black students, seem to be more competitive, that in a matter of relatively short period of time, that the balance, the percentage of students today now will be pretty well in proportion to the percentage
of blacks that graduate from Texas high schools, for example.
So in other words, we feel like we're getting our fair share.
But it's just that we need to, even though we might have a right percentage of the pie, the pie needs to be bigger.
And that's the answer, really, is to graduate more black and Hispanic students
that are competitive that we can accept.
So does this go back to improving high schools in Texas?
Oh, yes.
And increasing integration?
You bet.
That's just basic.
And I think we've done a fairly good job of that.
It's just that you can't go from dead still to wide open instantly.
It takes time.
Oh, sure.
And people are impatient with the passing of time.
But it passes whether you're impatient or not.
So we'll get there.
And I would imagine that this is the same reason that we have a difficult time attracting minority faculty members.
Same deal exactly.
Competition.
We were talking about some specific disciplines that we needed.
I've forgotten what it was, but it was a scientific, I believe it was in the College of Medicine.
They were interested in getting a black faculty member in a certain discipline.
And it was determined at that time there was only one black guy in the entire state of Texas that practiced that particular discipline.
And he was working somewhere else.
So you've got to have a universe to draw from before you've got a fighting chance.
And the universe just hasn't been there up until relatively recent years.
And that's a failure of our education system, a past failure, which we're attempting to remedy.
And I think we are remedying that.

But a black student that entered the first grade with white students that's integrated all the way, then you should have every reason to assume that when they graduate from high school that the black students is going to be just as competitive as the white students.
Now, that's not so now because it hadn't been that way from the first grade.
The pipeline's got to run a while before you get good clear water coming out the end.
And so it's running, and we'll get there.
But in the meantime, we just got to do the best we can
Be competitive.
And I think our summer school program is a wonderful program in that we will let anyone in to our summer school program regardless of class standing and regardless of SAT scores.
Yeah, that is a nice one.
And then if they hack it, some people just by sheer guts can take a losing situation and turn it into a winning situation because they want to bad enough.
And that program has been wonderful.
Give everybody a chance.
We don't plan on changing that, do we?
Not to my knowledge.
Of course, you're talking in the academic area now, which is not my area.
So all I can give you is just man on the street hearsay type answers to academic type questions.
Yeah, I think that's an outstanding program.
Very necessary program.
Now, we've talked about changes at A&M.
We've talked about your military career and your ideas of leadership and your background.
Is there something in this oral biography that you think that I've left out that you think that we should talk about?
Basically, I'm out of questions.
Okay.
Is there some aspect that I didn't cover?
Because you're the expert on your life.
I might just ramble a few minutes, if I may.
Fine.
And tell you some of the things that are important in my life.
Okay, good.
To me, I try to, as best I can, and I realize that it's not possible to do this, but I try to compartmentalize my life.
Mm-hmm.
in the time compartments.

When I go home, and I usually go home pretty close to 5 o'clock, 5.15, 5.30 or so, unless there's something pushing me, I try to forget what's at work, and then I concentrate on things that I do at home.
I'm a big time scheduler.
I've got a time to do this and a time to do that.
And I stick to it usually pretty well.
